## Important constraints:

1. Do NOT call `c.Render()` — the Fiber test app should NOT have a template engine. Any handler that calls `c.Render` will error. For those handlers, the test should check the status code or JSON body only, OR if the handler returns a redirect, follow that.

2. The real handlers do call `c.Render`. To handle this: build the test app WITHOUT the HTML engine. When a handler tries to render a template, it will return an error. You can work around this in two ways:
   - For handlers that redirect (like POST /login success → redirect to /dashboard), just test the redirect status code (302/303) — no template rendered
   - For handlers that should render a page, test them with HTMX headers (`HX-Request: true`) so they return JSON/partial responses instead of full-page renders, OR mock the render to return 200
   - Actually: check if handlers have a path that returns JSON for HTMX requests — if so, test via HTMX mode

3. Alternative approach (better): Create the test Fiber app WITH the template engine but pointing to the actual `web/templates` directory (use relative path `../../web/templates`). This is more realistic. Check if the template dir exists in tests.

4. For POST forms, use `Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded` and encode body accordingly.

5. Sessions: The auth middleware reads a `session_token` cookie. The loginAs helper must:
   - Call POST /login via app.Test()
   - Extract the Set-Cookie header
   - Return the cookie string for use in subsequent requests

6. All tests in `integration_test` package (external test package).

7. After writing, verify `go test ./internal/integration/...` compiles. It's ok if some tests that need template rendering are skipped or are expected to fail with template errors — add a comment explaining why.

Write complete, compilable test code. Do not guess at constructor signatures — read the actual source files first."}

